The Surinam Aluminum Company(SURALCO) registered a 75 pct drop in alumina exports inFebruary after its operations were shut down by worker violenceand guerrilla sabotage, the official Surinam News Agency, SNA,reported.    SNA said Suralco's alumina exports dropped to 23,869 tonnesin February from 92,852 tonnes in January. Aluminum exports,meanwhile, decreased nine pct in the same period, to 1,511tonnes from 1,647 tonnes.    Suralco's alumina refinery at Paranam, 18 miles south ofthe capital, was shut down February 2 after workers destroyedplant and computer equipment in a protest over layoffs at thecompany's nearby aluminum smelter.    The smelter was shut down January 26 after anti-governmentguerrillas dynamited two electricity towers which transmitpower to the plant from the Afobaka dam.    The alumina refinery, owned jointly by Suralco and BillitonNV, a Royal Dutch Shell subsidiary, was reopened March 9. Butthe smelter remains closed, as do the Suralco mines at Moengo,60 miles east of Paramaribo, which were closed down byguerrillas last November. Reuter&#3;